Global Music Final

Elizabeth Healy

Introduction

The music industry is extremely competitive which makes it hard to stand out especially if youre a new musician trying to break into the scene. If popularity is ones primary goal when creating music, well then I might be able to help! I will take an objective look at what makes a track popular. In this project, I will analyze, clean, and visualize the data set for global music. The global music data set is a collection of various artists, tracks, popularity of tracks, and the different characteristics for each track spanning over several decades.

Using R, I will perform an analysis and visualize the data to compare the characteristics with the most popular and least popular tracks. Perhaps certain characteristics may not have any correlation to how popular a track is while other characteristics may strongly dictate whether the track will be popular. I will also look at how older songs hold up to newer songs in popularity. With my analysis I hope to aid those in the music industry to determine whether a track is likely to be a hit or a flop.

To gain insights on what makes a track popular I will use the following steps:

  • Load required packages
  • Clean and prepare the data for analysis
  • Perform exploratory analysis
  • Summarize our findings

I used the following codes to analyze the variables in the source data. There are 23 variables, 32833 observations, and 15 missing values. There were 5 missing values each in track name, track artist, and track album name. Although these values are missing, we still have the values for the characteristics and popularity for these observations, thus it will not affect the analysis. My approach to finding duplicates in the data was by looking at the track IDs. If there are duplicates here, then it is highly likely that these observations are indeed duplicated since IDs should be unique to each observation.

For cleaning the data, I decided to remove variables that are not related to my focus. I did remove some characteristics such as mode, key, speechiness, and liveness as we determined that these would not provide significant information in determining popularity. Then I removed duplicates by the track_id since IDs should be unique to each observation. Additionally, having the duration of songs be in milliseconds is not very intuitive, so I changed this variable to be in minutes and then changed the variable name to be duration. There were 6 values in the variable loudness that were outside the range (0 to -60) that loudness is measured in. To keep these variables within the range without entirely removing the observation, I changed all values that were greater than 0 to the median of the loudness variable. Lastly, I converted the track album release date variable to a date format and created a new variable called release year and extracted just the year. I then removed the track album release date since we now have the year and the months/days isnt as important.

# Cleaning the data

#Remove duplicates
clean_music <- music_data[!duplicated(music_data$track_id), ]
duplicated(clean_music$track_id)
str(clean_music)

# Remove unnecessary/unused variables
clean_music <- select(clean_music, -c(track_id, track_album_id, playlist_id, track_name, track_artist, track_album_name, playlist_name, playlist_subgenre, playlist_genre, key, mode, speechiness, liveness ))



# Change variable "duration_ms" from milliseconds to minutes, rename, & round
clean_music$duration_ms <- ((clean_music$duration_ms/1000)/60)  
clean_music <- rename(clean_music, duration = duration_ms) 
round(clean_music$duration, digits = 2)


# Data Imputation - Look at values outside of variable range and change to median
filter(clean_music, loudness > 0)
clean_music$loudness[clean_music$loudness == 1.275] <- median(clean_music$loudness, na.rm = TRUE)
clean_music$loudness[clean_music$loudness == 0.551] <- median(clean_music$loudness, na.rm = TRUE)
clean_music$loudness[clean_music$loudness == 0.326] <- median(clean_music$loudness, na.rm = TRUE)
clean_music$loudness[clean_music$loudness == 0.642] <- median(clean_music$loudness, na.rm = TRUE)
clean_music$loudness[clean_music$loudness == 1.135] <- median(clean_music$loudness, na.rm = TRUE)
clean_music$loudness[clean_music$loudness == 0.302] <- median(clean_music$loudness, na.rm = TRUE)

# Convert to Date & extract year

clean_music$track_album_release_date <- sub(".*(\\d+{4}).*$", "\\1", clean_music$track_album_release_date)
clean_music <- rename(clean_music, release_year = track_album_release_date) 
summary(clean_music)
sum(is.na(clean_music$release_year))
unique(clean_music$release_year)
clean_music$release_year <- as.Date(clean_music$release_year, "%Y")
clean_music$release_year <- year(clean_music$release_year)
summary(clean_music$release_year)
# Verify all changes have been made
summary(clean_music) # Show all Variables are within range
str(clean_music) # Show all duplicated values (less observations)

Exploratory Analysis

The first step to uncover information in the data was to create new variables. The first variable I created was track ratings which separated different ratings into either bottom, fair, moderate, satisfactory, or top tracks. The second variable I created was era which categorized release years into either pre-2000s, early 2000s, or current (ranging from 2015-2020). Having these new variables makes visualizing the data more efficient and easier to identify trends.

To visualize the impact of characteristics on popularity of tracks, I created boxplots that used the specific characteristics compared to the track ratings and the era in which it was released. Two characteristics,instrumentalness and valence, did not give enough information with boxplots, thus I created additional graphs to gain further insights.

To visualize the impact duration has on popularity, I decided to only compare the bottom tracks and top tracks in track ratings with duration using histograms. This process allowed me to simplify the data while maintaining the focus on my primary goal of answering what makes a track popular.

Creating New Variables

#Adding new variable that categorizes track popularity ratings 
clean_music <- clean_music %>% 
  mutate(track_ratings = case_when((track_popularity < 10) ~ "bottom tracks",
         (track_popularity >= 10) & (track_popularity < 50) ~ "fair tracks",
         (track_popularity >= 50) & (track_popularity < 75) ~ "moderate tracks",
         (track_popularity >= 75) & (track_popularity < 90) ~ "satisfactory tracks",
         (track_popularity >= 90) ~ "top tracks"))
#Check how many counts for each category
table(clean_music$track_ratings)

clean_music <- clean_music %>% 
  mutate(era = case_when((release_year < 2000) ~ "Pre-2000s",
         (release_year >= 2000) & (release_year < 2015) ~ "early 2000s",
         (release_year >= 2015) ~ "Current (2015-Now)"))

Characteristics by Era & Popularity Plots

Energy

In all eras, the top rated tracks all had lower energy levels than the other rated groups, with the exception of the early 2000s being relatively the same as fair tracks. Outside of the top most rated tracks and the current era, the correlation between energy and track ratings is not super clear.

clean_music %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = track_ratings, y = energy))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~era) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Energy by Track Popularity Rating & Era")+
  labs(x = " ", y = "Energy")

Danceability

Current tracks are more popular the more dance-able it is, and the opposite is true for the early 2000s tracks. With the pre-2000s tracks, there is no identifiable correlation between track ratings and danceability.

clean_music %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = track_ratings, y = danceability)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~era) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Danceability by Track Popularity Rating & Era")+
  labs(x = " ", y = "Danceability")

Loudness

It is immediately obvious that loudness does not vary significantly between tracks but there is a slight indication that the less loud a track is the higher the popularity. However, weve concluded that overall loudness does not have any significant bearing on how popular a track is.

clean_music %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = track_ratings, y = loudness)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~era) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Loudness by Track Popularity Rating & Era")+
  labs(x = " ", y = "Loudness")

Acousticness

In both the current and pre-2000s eras, as acousticness goes up, so does the popularity. In the early 2000s tracks, only the bottom tracks had slightly less acousticness. Thus we concluded that more acousticness does indicate that a track will be more popular.

clean_music %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = track_ratings, y = acousticness)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~era) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Acousticness by Track Popularity Rating & Era")+
  labs(x = " ", y = "Acousticness")

Instrumentalness

The boxplots are not giving us much information with how popularity, instrumentalness, and eras correlate. We can see that all tracks have around the same range of instrumentalness, which is close to zero. To look further into this I created a scatterplot comparing just the instrumentalness and track popularity. I decided to take the top 15,000 tracks to have enough data to come to a conclusion. Adding a trend line helps us see where most of the distribution lies and how instrumentalness plays a role in popularity.

We see that tracks that have a higher instrumentalness characteristic to them are less popular and only the top most rated tracks have an instrumentalness of near zero (aside from a couple of outliers).

clean_music %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = track_ratings, y = instrumentalness)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~era) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Instrumentalness by Track Popularity Rating & Era")+
  labs(x = " ",  y = "Instrumentalness")

#Instrument Graph without era

#Looking at how Track Popularity and Instrumentalness Correlate;

top_15000_most_popular_with_instrumentalness <- clean_music %>%

  select(track_popularity, instrumentalness) %>%

  scale_y_continuous(name = "Instrumentalness")

Valence

Current tracks are more popular the higher the valence is, but with early and pre-2000s tracks, the most popular tracks had lower valence than the bottom tracks. One thing we found interesting was how the overall valence has gone down in current tracks compared to the other eras so we wanted to dig a little deeper into this by creating histograms of just valence and eras without the popularity ratings.

The histograms show that the majority of tracks in the current era have a valence of around .30 whereas early 2000s tracks were mostly around .55 and the pre-2000s tracks had an even higher majority valence of around .70. This shows that tracks, regardless of popularity, are trending with lower valence, meaning less happy/cheerful and more sad/depressing.

clean_music %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = track_ratings, y = valence)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~era) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Valence by Track Popularity Rating & Era")+
  labs(x = " ", y = "Valence")

Duration Plots

Bottom Tracks

The majority of the tracks with the lowest popularity ratings have a duration of around 3.5 - 4 minutes. There were many tracks that were 5 minutes or longer and even some tracks were less than 2 minutes long.

#Creating data frame with just top tracks and duration
bottom_duration <- clean_music %>% 
  filter(track_ratings == "bottom tracks") %>% 
  select(track_ratings, duration)


ggplot(data = bottom_duration, aes(x = duration)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 13, color = "orange")+
  ggtitle("Duration of Least Popular Tracks", subtitle = "Frequency of Bottom Track Durations")+
  labs(x = "Duration", y = "Number of Tracks")

Top Tracks

The majority of the tracks with the highest popularity ratings were around 2.75 to 4.25 minutes long with no songs going over the 5.5 minute mark.

#Creating data frame with just top tracks and duration
top_duration<- clean_music %>% 
  filter(track_ratings == "top tracks") %>% 
  select(track_ratings, duration)

ggplot(data = top_duration, aes(x = duration)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 6, color = "yellow") +
  ggtitle("Duration of Most Popular Tracks", subtitle = "Frequency of Top Track Durations")+
  labs(x = "Duration", y = "Number of Tracks")

Summary of Findings

I wanted to find the characteristics that determined a tracks popularity rating and whether the duration of the track played a role in its popularity. I also sought out to find any obvious trends of how music has changed over time. I discovered that danceability, loudness, and tempo were not great indicators on determining whether a track will be popular, with the exception of current tracks having a preference of a higher danceability measure. Energy is also not a great indicator, however, I found that it does show a trend that more recent tracks are higher rated when energy is lower and around .60-.65 on the scale.

Acousticness showed a definite trend that the higher the confidence measure of acoustics in a track, the higher it was rated. And with instrumentalness, tracks were rated significantly higher the closer the instrumentalness got to zero.

What I found most interesting in the exploratory analysis was how valence has changed over time. The higher the valence is, the higher the track is rated, but valence in tracks have been trending down over the years. It seems artists are creating more sad and depressing songs which could indicate the overall general mood of society. This is of course outside the scope of my analysis, but something I felt worth noting.

As for duration, most tracks, regardless of popularity, ran around 3-4 minutes long. However, only the most popular tracks did not ever exceed 5.5 minutes or fell below 2 minutes long.

My suggestion for those in the music industry is to create tracks that have a good amount of acoustics and vocals. The track should be around 3.5 minutes long and have a mellow vibe that is neither too happy or too sad.

Final notes:

If I were to build onto this data to improve it, it would be insightful to see the popularity of the tracks at the time it was released, rather than just how popular the tracks are today. This would give a clearer picture of how the music industry has evolved over time and what music consumers were looking for then and what they are looking for now.
